3. User Manual
3.1 Overview
F-CTF is a Capture The Flag platform that supports the full lifecycle of challenge operation, from challenge authoring and secure deployment to contestant solving and support tickets.
The platform includes two main portals:
- Control Center (Admin and Challenge Writer): create and configure challenges, deploy challenge runtime environments, monitor instances, and maintain challenge metadata.
- Contestant Portal (Players): browse challenges, start challenge instances, access services using challenge tokens, submit flags, manage running instances, and create support tickets.

Section 3 documents the two operational workflows used most frequently in production:
- Workflow A: Admin and Challenge Writer challenge management lifecycle.
- Workflow B: Contestant challenge participation and support lifecycle.

3.2 Core Workflows
3.2.1 Workflow A - Admin and Challenge Writer: Challenge Management Lifecycle
Purpose:
- Guide Admin/Challenge Writer through challenge creation, deployment setup, testing, release operation, and monitoring.

High-level flow:
Manage Challenges -> Create Challenge -> Configure Options/Deploy -> Verify Deployment -> Manage Metadata -> View Deploy History -> Preview -> Start Shared Instance (if enabled) -> Monitor/Stop Instances

Step-by-step guide:
Step 1 - Create a new challenge
- Open Manage Challenges and click [+ Create Challenge].
- Select challenge type:
    - Standard: fixed score.
    - Dynamic: score decays based on solve count.
    - Multiple choice: one correct option from predefined choices.
- Fill required fields: Name, Category, Value.
- Fill optional fields as needed: Difficulty, Files, Description, Time Limit, Max Attempts, Submission Cooldown.
- For Dynamic challenges, provide Initial Value, Decay Function, Decay, and Minimum Value.
- For Multiple choice challenges, enter choices in list format and define the correct answer.

Step 2 - Configure challenge options
- Click [Create] to open the options dialog.
- Configure:
    - Flags (case-sensitive or case-insensitive as required).
    - Setup Deploy (enable if runtime environment is required).
    - Challenge attachments for contestants.
    - Visibility (Visible or Hidden).
- Click [Finish] to save the challenge.

Step 3 - Configure deployment (for deployable challenges)
- Provide deployment parameters:
    - Expose Port (required).
    - Connection Protocol (HTTP/TCP or as designed).
    - CPU Limit/Request and Memory Limit/Request.
    - gVisor runtime option.
    - Harden Container option for restricted security posture.
    - Max Deploy Count (0 = unlimited).
    - Shared Instance mode (one shared runtime for all contestants).
    - Deploy File (required ZIP source package).

Step 4 - Verify deployment and configure challenge metadata
- On Challenge Detail, verify deployment status and latest deployment timestamp.
- Configure additional tabs:
    - Challenge Files: downloadable files.
    - Flags: static/regex flags.
    - Topics and Tags: challenge classification.
    - Hints: optional hints with point cost and dependencies.
    - Requirements: prerequisite challenge and lock behavior (Hidden/Anonymized).
    - Deploy: deployment configuration updates.
    - Versions: active/old image versions and rollback.
    - Next: next challenge recommendation after solve.

Step 5 - Review deploy history and logs
- In Manage Challenges, open [Actions] -> [History].
- Use [View Details] to inspect workflow logs for each deployment.

Step 6 - Run preview mode for validation
- In Manage Challenges, open [Actions] -> [Preview].
- Wait for preview deployment completion and retrieve preview token.
- Access the challenge as a contestant using the issued token.

Step 7 - Operate shared instance and monitor running instances
- For Shared Instance challenges, Admin must manually start the shared runtime with [Actions] -> [Start].
- Use Monitoring screen to track instance ownership, category, status, token, and end time.
- Admin actions in Monitoring: Pod Logs, Request Logs, Stop Instance.

3.2.2 Workflow B - Contestant: Challenge Participation and Support Lifecycle
Purpose:
- Guide contestants from login to challenge solving, instance management, and support ticket handling.

High-level flow:
Login -> Browse Challenges -> Open Challenge -> Start Instance -> Access Service with Token -> Submit Flag -> Manage Instances -> Create/Track Tickets

Step-by-step guide:
Step 1 - Log in
- Open Contestant Portal.
- Sign in using the provided username and password.

Step 2 - Browse and select a challenge
- Open Challenges page and choose a category (for example: PWN, Web, Crypto).
- Open the target challenge detail.

Step 3 - Start challenge instance (for deployable challenges)
- Click [+ Start Challenge] to request instance deployment.
- Review challenge card data:
    - Points.
    - Time limit (countdown after successful deployment).
    - Attempt limit.
    - Deploy count (current/maximum).
    - Attachments for download.

Step 4 - Access challenge service
- After deployment, obtain access token and connection details.
- HTTP mode:
    - Open URL: http://<gateway-host>:<http-port>?fctftoken=<YOUR_TOKEN>
- TCP mode:
    - Connect: nc <gateway-host> <tcp-port>
    - Enter token when prompted.

Step 5 - Submit flag
- Enter discovered flag in the submission field.
- Click [SUBMIT].
- If correct, the system records solve status and awards points.

Step 6 - Manage running instances
- Open [Instances] from the menu.
- Review challenge name, category, token, status, and finish time.
- Available actions:
    - [GO]: return to challenge detail.
    - [STOP]: terminate instance with confirmation.
    - [REFRESH]: reload latest status.

Step 7 - Create and manage support tickets
- Open [Tickets] to view ticket list (ID, Title, Type, Date, Status).
- Click [+ NEW TICKET] to create a ticket with Title, Type, and Description.
- Use [VIEW] to read ticket details and organizer responses.
- Delete rule: only Open tickets can be deleted; Closed tickets are protected from deletion.

3.3 Guideline for writing Challenge 
3.3.1 Challenge Folder Structure
Each challenge must be packaged in a separate folder containing all the source code and resources required to build and run the challenge. Inside this folder, a Dockerfile must be placed at the root directory. The system will use this Dockerfile to build the container image for the challenge.
All other files and directories within the challenge folder can be defined by the challenge author. These may include source code, libraries, configuration files, or any additional resources required for the challenge to function properly. The entire folder will be used as the build context when building the container image.
Example folder structure:
challenge-name/
├── Dockerfile
└── (other files and folders defined by the challenge author)
 
Figure 0 1: Challenge Folder Structure
After preparing the challenge folder, compress it into a .zip file so it can be uploaded to the F-CTF system following the Create Challenge guideline.
3.3.2 Dockerfile Guideline
If the Harden Container option is not enabled, the Dockerfile only needs to ensure that the challenge runs correctly inside the container, and there are no additional security requirements. However, enabling the Harden Container option is recommended to improve the security of the challenge environment.
The following section provides recommended Dockerfile practices for challenges using the Harden Container option, helping authors design containers that comply with these security constraints while maintaining proper functionality.
3.3.2.1 Mandatory Requirements
All challenge Dockerfiles must strictly comply with the following constraints.
Violation of any requirement may cause the container to be rejected or crash when deployed in the Kubernetes environment.
Requirement	Description
USER 1000	The container must run with UID = 1000. The Dockerfile must end with USER 1000.
Read-only root filesystem	The root filesystem is mounted read-only at runtime. The application must not require write access to the root filesystem.
Write only to /tmp	The container must not write outside /tmp. Writing to /data, /var, /etc, /home, or other directories is not allowed. All temporary storage must use /tmp (mounted as tmpfs).
Logs → stdout/stderr	File-based logging is not allowed. All logs must be written to stdout or stderr so that Kubernetes can collect them.
Single port only	The container must expose and listen on exactly one port, as defined in the challenge specification.
No Linux capabilities	The container must not require additional Linux capabilities. Do not use setcap, privileged mode, or add extra capabilities.
Mandatory runtime test	The container must successfully run with the following command before submission: docker run --read-only --tmpfs /tmp --user 1000 <image>
Table 0 1: Mandatory Requirements for Dockerfile
3.3.2.2 Dockerfile Design Strategy
•	Keep the runtime immutable: everything in the root filesystem must be read-only.
•	Use /tmp symlinks for all runtime files that require write access (logs, temp files, working directories).
•	Standardize the runtime user by either using a base image with UID 1000 or explicitly creating a user with adduser -u 1000.
•	Separate build-time and runtime tasks whenever possible. For example, extract artifacts (WAR/JAR) during the build stage.
•	Ensure all necessary files and directories are owned by UID 1000 before switching to the runtime user.
Step	Action
1	Choose a suitable base image (Alpine is preferred due to its small size).
2	Create or configure a user with UID 1000.
3	Install required dependencies during the build stage.
4	Copy the source code or application artifact into the image.
5	Create symlinks to /tmp for any directories that require write access at runtime.
6	Set ownership for the application directory: chown -R 1000:1000.
7	Switch to the runtime user using USER 1000.
8	Define the startup command, typically: CMD mkdir -p /tmp/... && exec <server>
Table 0 2: Steps to write a Dockerfile
Note: A key design pattern is that symlinks must be created during the build stage, when the filesystem is still writable. At runtime, the container should only need to create directories under /tmp, typically using: `mkdir -p /tmp/<target>` inside the CMD or entrypoint before starting the application.
3.3.2.3 Detailed Templates by Workload Type
Each workload type below provides a ready-to-use Dockerfile template. The templates use placeholders in the format <>, simply replace them with your actual values (application name, paths, ports, etc.) before using them. Each template is followed by a fully filled example to illustrate how it should be applied in practice.
How to Use the Templates: All fields written as <> are placeholders. Replace them with your actual values before building the image.
Example:
<PORT> => 8080
<APP_USER> => appuser
<SRC_DIR> => ./html
3.3.2.3.1 Static Server - Nginx
By default, Nginx writes logs and PID files outside /tmp, which violates the hardened container constraints. Therefore, the template uses sed to directly modify the existing nginx.conf inside the image, eliminating the need to provide a custom configuration file.
TEMPLATE
FROM nginx:alpine

# [CUSTOMIZABLE] 1. Declare User and Port (can also be overridden via --build-arg)
ARG APP_USER=appuser
ARG PORT=8080

RUN adduser -D -u 1000 $APP_USER

# 2. Remove default configuration
RUN rm -rf /etc/nginx/conf.d/default.conf

# [CUSTOMIZABLE] 3. Create new server configuration
# You may change the root directory or index file here if necessary
RUN echo "server { \
    listen ${PORT}; \
    location / { \
        root /usr/share/nginx/html; \
        index index.html; \
        try_files \$uri \$uri/ =404; \
    } \
}" > /etc/nginx/conf.d/default.conf

# 4. Force Nginx to use /tmp for ALL writable paths
RUN sed -i 's|pid .*|pid /tmp/nginx.pid;|' /etc/nginx/nginx.conf \
    && sed -i 's|access_log .*|access_log /dev/stdout;|' /etc/nginx/nginx.conf \
    && sed -i 's|error_log .*|error_log /dev/stderr;|' /etc/nginx/nginx.conf \
    && sed -i "/http {/a \    client_body_temp_path /tmp/client_temp;\n    proxy_temp_path /tmp/proxy_temp;\n    fastcgi_temp_path /tmp/fastcgi_temp;\n    uwsgi_temp_path /tmp/uwsgi_temp;\n    scgi_temp_path /tmp/scgi_temp;" /etc/nginx/nginx.conf \
    && sed -i 's/^user/#user/' /etc/nginx/nginx.conf

# [CUSTOMIZABLE] 5. Copy Source Code into the Image
# Replace <SRC_DIR> with your source directory (e.g., ./dist, ./html, ./public)
COPY <SRC_DIR> /usr/share/nginx/html

# 6. Fix permissions (important: avoid chown /var/run to prevent Kaniko/K8s issues)
RUN chown -R 1000:1000 /usr/share/nginx/html /etc/nginx /var/cache/nginx

USER 1000
EXPOSE ${PORT}

# 7. Startup: create temporary directories inside /tmp
CMD ["sh", "-c", "mkdir -p /tmp/client_temp /tmp/proxy_temp /tmp/fastcgi_temp /tmp/uwsgi_temp /tmp/scgi_temp && exec nginx -g 'daemon off;'"]

EXAMPLE - Static HTML, Port 8080
FROM nginx:alpine

# 1. Create a non-root user (UID 1000)
RUN adduser -D -u 1000 appuser

# 2. Remove the default Nginx configuration
RUN rm -rf /etc/nginx/conf.d/default.conf

# 3. Create a new server configuration
RUN echo 'server { \
    listen 8080; \
    location / { \
        root /usr/share/nginx/html; \
        index index.html; \
    } \
}' > /etc/nginx/conf.d/default.conf

# 4. Modify the main Nginx configuration to force all writable paths into /tmp
# Add uwsgi and scgi temporary paths as well
RUN sed -i 's|pid .*|pid /tmp/nginx.pid;|' /etc/nginx/nginx.conf \
    && sed -i 's|access_log .*|access_log /dev/stdout;|' /etc/nginx/nginx.conf \
    && sed -i 's|error_log .*|error_log /dev/stderr;|' /etc/nginx/nginx.conf \
    && sed -i '/http {/a \    client_body_temp_path /tmp/client_temp;\n    proxy_temp_path /tmp/proxy_temp;\n    fastcgi_temp_path /tmp/fastcgi_temp;\n    uwsgi_temp_path /tmp/uwsgi_temp;\n    scgi_temp_path /tmp/scgi_temp;' /etc/nginx/nginx.conf \
    && sed -i 's/^user/#user/' /etc/nginx/nginx.conf

# 5. Copy application files
COPY ./html /usr/share/nginx/html

# 6. Set permissions (avoid touching /var/run to prevent Kaniko/K8s issues)
RUN chown -R 1000:1000 /usr/share/nginx/html /etc/nginx /var/cache/nginx

# Run container as non-root user
USER 1000

# Expose the application port
EXPOSE 8080

# 7. Startup command:
# Create all required temporary directories in /tmp before launching Nginx
CMD ["sh", "-c", "mkdir -p /tmp/client_temp /tmp/proxy_temp /tmp/fastcgi_temp /tmp/uwsgi_temp /tmp/scgi_temp && exec nginx -g 'daemon off;'"]

3.3.2.3.2 Node.js Backend
TEMPLATE
# Debian slim supports building native modules (e.g., sqlite3)
# <NODE_VER> example: 18
FROM node:<NODE_VER>-bullseye-slim

WORKDIR /app

# Optional build dependencies
RUN apt-get update && \
    apt-get install -y python3 build-essential --no-install-recommends && \
    rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*

# Install production dependencies
COPY package*.json ./
RUN npm install --production

COPY . .

# Redirect writable paths to /tmp
RUN rm -rf <WRITE_PATH_1> && ln -s /tmp/<TMP_NAME_1> <WRITE_PATH_1> || true
RUN rm -rf <WRITE_PATH_2> && ln -s /tmp/<TMP_NAME_2> <WRITE_PATH_2> || true
RUN rm -f <DB_FILE>      && ln -s /tmp/<DB_FILE>      <DB_FILE>      || true

# Create user 1000
RUN groupadd -g 1000 appgroup || true && \
    useradd -r -u 1000 -g appgroup -m -d /home/<APP_USER> -s /usr/sbin/nologin <APP_USER> || true

RUN mkdir -p /tmp/<TMP_NAME_1> /tmp/<TMP_NAME_2> && \
    chown -R 1000:1000 /tmp /app

ENV PORT=<PORT>
ENV TMPDIR=/tmp
ENV NODE_ENV=production

EXPOSE <PORT>

USER 1000

CMD ["sh","-c","mkdir -p /tmp/<TMP_NAME_1> /tmp/<TMP_NAME_2> && exec node <ENTRY_FILE>"]

