b, Spring Boot
Spring Boot applications should use a multi-stage build:
•	Build stage: Use Maven to compile the application.
•	Runtime stage: Use a lightweight JRE image to run the application.
If the application depends on native libraries (e.g., SQLite JDBC), these libraries should be extracted from the JAR during the build stage and placed into /usr/lib.
This ensures the JVM can load them without needing to write files to the root filesystem at runtime.
TEMPLATE
# ── Build stage ──────────────────────────────────────────
FROM maven:3.9-eclipse-temurin-<JDK_VER> AS build
WORKDIR /build
COPY pom.xml .
COPY src ./src
RUN mvn -q -DskipTests package

# (Optional) Extract native libraries to avoid runtime writes to /tmp
# Example for sqlite-jdbc - adjust version to match pom.xml
RUN mkdir -p /native && \
    jar xf target/*.jar BOOT-INF/lib/<NATIVE_LIB>.jar && \
    jar xf BOOT-INF/lib/<NATIVE_LIB>.jar org/sqlite/native/Linux/x86_64/libsqlitejdbc.so && \
    mv org/sqlite/native/Linux/x86_64/libsqlitejdbc.so /native/libsqlitejdbc.so

# ── Runtime stage ────────────────────────────────────────
# Use Debian-based JRE to avoid musl libc issues with native libraries
FROM eclipse-temurin:<JDK_VER>-jre

WORKDIR /app

# Copy native libraries (optional)
COPY --from=build /native/libsqlitejdbc.so /usr/lib/libsqlitejdbc.so

COPY --from=build /build/target/*.jar /app/app.jar

USER 1000

ENV JAVA_TOOL_OPTIONS="\
    -Djava.io.tmpdir=/tmp \
    -Dorg.sqlite.lib.path=/usr/lib \
    -Dorg.sqlite.lib.name=libsqlitejdbc.so"

EXPOSE <PORT>

CMD ["java", "-jar", "/app/app.jar", "--server.port=<PORT>"]

EXAMPLE - Spring Boot + SQLite, port 8080
# ── Build stage ──────────────────────────────────────────
FROM maven:3.9-eclipse-temurin-17 AS build
WORKDIR /build
COPY pom.xml .
COPY src ./src
RUN mvn -q -DskipTests package

RUN mkdir -p /native && \
    jar xf target/*.jar BOOT-INF/lib/sqlite-jdbc-3.49.1.0.jar && \
    jar xf BOOT-INF/lib/sqlite-jdbc-3.49.1.0.jar org/sqlite/native/Linux/x86_64/libsqlitejdbc.so && \
    mv org/sqlite/native/Linux/x86_64/libsqlitejdbc.so /native/libsqlitejdbc.so

# ── Runtime stage ────────────────────────────────────────
FROM eclipse-temurin:17-jre

WORKDIR /app

COPY --from=build /native/libsqlitejdbc.so /usr/lib/libsqlitejdbc.so
COPY --from=build /build/target/*.jar /app/app.jar

USER 1000

ENV JAVA_TOOL_OPTIONS="\
    -Djava.io.tmpdir=/tmp \
    -Dorg.sqlite.lib.path=/usr/lib \
    -Dorg.sqlite.lib.name=libsqlitejdbc.so"

EXPOSE 8080

CMD ["java", "-jar", "/app/app.jar", "--server.port=8080"]

3.3.2.3.5 .NET (ASP.NET Core)
ASP.NET Core applications should use a multi-stage build:
•	Build stage: Use the .NET SDK image to compile and publish the application. 
•	Runtime stage: Use the lightweight ASP.NET runtime image to run the application. 
If the application uses sessions, cookies, or authentication, the DataProtection key storage must be configured to use a writable location (e.g., /tmp), since the root filesystem is read-only in the challenge environment.
TEMPLATE
# ── Stage 1: Build ──────────────────────────────────────
FROM mcr.microsoft.com/dotnet/sdk:<DOTNET_VER>-alpine AS build
WORKDIR /src

COPY *.csproj ./
RUN dotnet restore

COPY . .
RUN dotnet publish -c Release -o /app/publish \
    --self-contained false /p:UseAppHost=false

# ── Stage 2: Runtime ─────────────────────────────────────
FROM mcr.microsoft.com/dotnet/aspnet:<DOTNET_VER>-alpine AS runtime

RUN adduser -D -u 1000 <APP_USER>

WORKDIR /app
COPY --from=build /app/publish .

# Redirect writable paths to /tmp
RUN rm -rf <WRITE_PATH_DATA>    && ln -s /tmp/<TMP_DATA>    <WRITE_PATH_DATA>
RUN rm -rf <WRITE_PATH_UPLOADS> && ln -s /tmp/<TMP_UPLOADS> <WRITE_PATH_UPLOADS> || true
RUN rm -f /app/app.db           && ln -s /tmp/app.db        /app/app.db          || true

RUN mkdir -p /tmp/<TMP_DATA> /tmp/<TMP_UPLOADS> /tmp/dp-keys

RUN chown -R 1000:1000 /app

USER 1000

ENV ASPNETCORE_URLS=http://+:<PORT>
ENV ASPNETCORE_ENVIRONMENT=Production
ENV TMPDIR=/tmp
ENV ASPNETCORE_DataProtection__KeyRingPath=/tmp/dp-keys

EXPOSE <PORT>

ENTRYPOINT ["dotnet","<DLL_NAME>.dll"]

EXAMPLE - ASP.NET 8, SQLite → /app/data, port 5000
FROM mcr.microsoft.com/dotnet/sdk:8.0-alpine AS build
WORKDIR /src

COPY *.csproj ./
RUN dotnet restore

COPY . .
RUN dotnet publish -c Release -o /app/publish \
    --self-contained false /p:UseAppHost=false

FROM mcr.microsoft.com/dotnet/aspnet:8.0-alpine

RUN adduser -D -u 1000 dotnetuser

WORKDIR /app
COPY --from=build /app/publish .

RUN rm -rf /app/data    && ln -s /tmp/app-data    /app/data
RUN rm -rf /app/uploads && ln -s /tmp/app-uploads /app/uploads
RUN rm -f /app/app.db   && ln -s /tmp/app.db      /app/app.db

RUN mkdir -p /tmp/app-data /tmp/app-uploads /tmp/dp-keys

RUN chown -R 1000:1000 /app
USER 1000

ENV ASPNETCORE_URLS=http://+:5000
ENV ASPNETCORE_ENVIRONMENT=Production
ENV TMPDIR=/tmp
ENV ASPNETCORE_DataProtection__KeyRingPath=/tmp/dp-keys

EXPOSE 5000

ENTRYPOINT ["dotnet","WebApplication2.dll"]

3.3.2.3.6	PHP (Apache)
It is mandatory to modify both: `ports.conf`, `000-default.conf` to use a port greater than 1024 (for example 8080).
This prevents Permission Denied errors when Apache runs as non-root user (UID 1000) in Kubernetes. Adding ServerName localhost also ensures the container starts faster and with cleaner logs.
TEMPLATE
# 1. Base Image: Choose an appropriate PHP version
# <PHP_VER> examples: 8.2, 8.1, 7.4
FROM php:<PHP_VER>-apache

# 2. Install System Packages (Optional)
# Add any libraries required for the challenge (SQLite, GD, Zip, etc.)
RUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y \
    libsqlite3-dev sqlite3 \
    && rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*

# 3. Install PHP Extensions (Optional)
# <EXTENSIONS> examples: pdo_sqlite, pdo_mysql, gd
RUN docker-php-ext-install <EXTENSIONS>

# 4. Configure Port & ServerName (Hardening)
# Replace <PORT> with the desired port (usually 8080 to allow non-root execution)
RUN sed -i 's/Listen 80/Listen <PORT>/' /etc/apache2/ports.conf \
    && sed -i 's/:80/:<PORT>/' /etc/apache2/sites-available/000-default.conf \
    && echo "ServerName localhost" >> /etc/apache2/apache2.conf

# 5. Force Apache to use /tmp for runtime writable paths (via environment variables)
ENV APACHE_RUN_DIR=/tmp/apache-run \
    APACHE_PID_FILE=/tmp/apache-run/apache2.pid \
    APACHE_LOCK_DIR=/tmp/apache-lock \
    APACHE_LOG_DIR=/tmp/apache-logs

# 6. Create a non-root user (UID 1000)
RUN groupadd -g 1000 appgroup || true && \
    useradd -r -u 1000 -g appgroup -m -d /home/appuser -s /usr/sbin/nologin appuser || true

# 7. Set permissions for Apache directories
# Allow user 1000 to read configs and write temporary logs
RUN chown -R 1000:1000 /var/www/html /etc/apache2 /var/lib/apache2 /var/log/apache2

WORKDIR /var/www/html

# 8. Copy source code
# <SRC_DIR> examples: ./src or .
COPY <SRC_DIR> .

# 9. Ensure all application files belong to user 1000
RUN chown -R 1000:1000 /var/www/html

USER 1000
EXPOSE <PORT>

# 10. Startup command: create required temporary directories under /tmp
# [Optional] Add database initialization if using SQLite
CMD ["sh", "-c", "mkdir -p $APACHE_RUN_DIR $APACHE_LOCK_DIR $APACHE_LOG_DIR /tmp/uploads && touch /tmp/data.db && exec apache2-foreground"]

EXAMPLE - PHP 8.2 + SQLite, Port 8080
FROM php:8.2-apache

# 1. Install dependencies
RUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y \
    libsqlite3-dev sqlite3 && rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*

RUN docker-php-ext-install pdo_sqlite

# 2. Configure Port & ServerName
RUN sed -i 's/Listen 80/Listen 8080/' /etc/apache2/ports.conf \
    && sed -i 's/:80/:8080/' /etc/apache2/sites-available/000-default.conf \
    && echo "ServerName localhost" >> /etc/apache2/apache2.conf

# 3. Apache runtime environment variables
ENV APACHE_RUN_DIR=/tmp/apache-run \
    APACHE_PID_FILE=/tmp/apache-run/apache2.pid \
    APACHE_LOCK_DIR=/tmp/apache-lock \
    APACHE_LOG_DIR=/tmp/apache-logs

# 4. Create non-root user
RUN groupadd -g 1000 appgroup || true && \
    useradd -r -u 1000 -g appgroup -m -d /home/appuser -s /usr/sbin/nologin appuser || true

# 5. Set permissions (removed /var/lib/php since it does not exist)
RUN chown -R 1000:1000 /var/www/html /etc/apache2 /var/lib/apache2 /var/log/apache2

WORKDIR /var/www/html
COPY . .

# Ensure all web files belong to user 1000
RUN chown -R 1000:1000 /var/www/html

USER 1000
EXPOSE 8080

# 6. Startup command
CMD ["sh","-c", "mkdir -p $APACHE_RUN_DIR $APACHE_LOCK_DIR $APACHE_LOG_DIR /tmp/uploads && touch /tmp/data.db && exec apache2-foreground"]

3.3.2.4 Anti-Patterns & Debugging
Common Anti-Patterns
Anti-Pattern	Correct Approach
Writing files to /app during runtime	Redirect writable paths to /tmp
Running container as root	Use USER 1000
Creating symlinks in CMD	Create them during build (RUN ln -s)
Logging to files	Use stdout or stderr
Using ports <1024	Use ports such as 8080, 5000, 3000
Table 0 3: Anti-Pattern for Hardern Dockerfile
Debugging
If the container crashes immediately after startup, check the logs:
docker logs <container_id>
Common causes include missing /tmp directories or permission issues.
For debugging, run the container interactively:
docker run -it --read-only --tmpfs /tmp --user 1000 <image> sh

Quick Local Test
Before uploading a challenge, test the container locally.
docker build -t challenge-x .
docker run --read-only --tmpfs /tmp --user 1000 -p <PORT>:<PORT> challenge-x
Note that passing this test does not guarantee compatibility with the F-CTF platform. The container should also be verified using the Preview feature before submission.


